(That's 13. If data quality is an issue for any of these over the 26-year window, document and substitute. Don't drop the instrument silently.)
Strategy variants
All three use the same 12-instrument basket, same vol-targeted sizing, same T-bill allocation for capital on currently-OFF instruments. They differ only in the trend signal logic.
Variant 1: Classic 50/200 SMA crossover
Same logic as the indices strategy. Each instrument independently:

ON when close > SMA(50) AND SMA(50) > SMA(200)
OFF otherwise

This is the baseline. It's well-validated on equity indices. The question for commodities is whether the same simple rule generalizes.
Variant 2: Donchian channel breakout (CTA-classic)
The original Turtle Trader signal, adapted for daily bars:

ON when close > highest close of trailing 100 days
OFF when close < lowest close of trailing 50 days
Asymmetric: slower exit than entry — gives positions room to breathe

This is the classic CTA trend signal that produced the 50-year track record of commodity trend-following. It catches different things than MA crossovers:

Breakouts to new highs (MA crossovers lag)
Asymmetric trend persistence (long trends in commodities can run further than equity trends)

Testing this variant answers: is the right signal for commodities different from what works on equities?
Variant 3: Vol-adjusted momentum
A momentum signal that explicitly accounts for volatility:

Compute 12-month return divided by 12-month realized volatility (Sharpe-style)
ON when this ratio is in the top 50% of its trailing 24-month range
OFF otherwise

This is the academic version of trend-following, used in most published research (Moskowitz, Ooi, Pedersen "Time Series Momentum"). It's different from the others because it considers magnitude relative to volatility, not just direction.
Testing this variant answers: does sophisticated trend signal beat simple price-based rules?
Position sizing (same for all three variants)
Vol-targeted, applied identically across variants so the comparison isolates signal differences.

Compute each instrument's 60-day realized volatility daily
Target portfolio annualized volatility: 15%
Each ON position sized so its contribution to portfolio vol is target_vol / (N_on × instrument_vol), where N_on is the count of currently-ON positions
Capital not deployed to commodity positions goes to T-bills earning current rates
Recompute position sizes daily as vol estimates change
Cap individual position size at 25% of portfolio to prevent single-instrument concentration

Capital allocation assumption for backtest
Model as if the strategy has its own dedicated allocation, not competing with the indices strategy. Start with $100k notional (large enough that integer-contract constraints don't dominate results). We'll address actual capital allocation between strategies after we see results.
Required infrastructure
Honest scoping needed before starting:

Continuous contract data for 13 commodities, 2000-2026. Back-adjusted methodology, consistent across instruments. Source likely CME for US contracts, ICE for Brent. Verify availability and data quality before committing. Some specific contracts (BZ Brent on CME, RBOB pre-2006) may have shorter histories — document where data starts for each.
Roll cost modeling per commodity. Each instrument rolls at different frequencies:


Energy contracts (CL, BZ, NG, HO, RB): typically monthly
Metals (GC, SI, HG): every 2 months
Grains (ZC, ZS, ZW): roll around contract expiry (3-4 month cycles)
Softs (SB, KC): variable

Use realistic per-roll bid-ask spread estimates from historical CME data. Energy rolls cost more (~5-10 bps), metals less (~2-5 bps).

Vol estimation module. 60-day rolling realized vol per instrument. Standard calculation: annualized standard deviation of daily log returns.
Multi-position book management. Track up to 13 simultaneous positions with individual states (ON/OFF), sizes, P&L, vol estimates. Portfolio-level aggregation.
Per-variant trend signal modules. Three separate signal generators (MA crossover, Donchian, vol-adjusted momentum), each producing daily ON/OFF flags per instrument.
Benchmark for comparison. Equal-weight commodity basket buy-and-hold over same period. This is the strategy's benchmark — does trend-following beat passive commodity exposure?

Backtest requirements
Standard framework, 26-year backtest (2000-2026), three sub-periods:

In-sample: 2018-2026
Held-out: 2010-2017
Regime-shift held-out: 2000-2009

For each variant, report:
Headline metrics:

Total return, CAGR, Sortino, Sharpe, max drawdown
After-tax CAGR (Section 1256 60/40 treatment for futures)
Win rate at trade level

Comparison to baselines:

Lift over equal-weight commodity basket buy-and-hold
Lift over indices strategy (the current locked baseline) for absolute return and Sortino

Diversification analysis:

Correlation of variant returns with indices strategy returns
Correlation matrix across the three variants (do they agree or trade different things?)
Per-sector contribution to total P&L
Behavior during specific equity bear regimes: 2000-2002, 2008, 2020-March, 2022

Diagnostic data:

Per-instrument Sortino and total contribution
Average position count over time (how diversified is the book at any given moment?)
Per-sub-period results (does any variant only work in one regime?)
Roll cost impact (what fraction of gross returns does rolling consume?)

Decision criteria (locked before seeing results)
Each variant gets evaluated independently against these criteria:
Tier A (clear deployment candidate):

Sortino > 1.5 across full 26-year sample
Sortino > 1.0 in each sub-period
Correlation with indices strategy < 0.3
Max drawdown < 25%
Robust across at least 4 of 6 sectors
Lift over equal-weight commodity buy-and-hold > 0.5 Sortino

Tier B (deployment candidate with caveats):

Sortino > 1.0 across full sample
Sortino > 0.7 in each sub-period
Correlation with indices strategy < 0.4
Max drawdown < 30%
Robust across at least 3 sectors
Lift over commodity buy-and-hold > 0.3 Sortino

Tier C (interesting but not deployment-ready):

Sortino > 0.7 across full sample
Either fails one Tier B criterion or shows period-specific weakness

Tier D: Anything else. Eliminated.
What we're looking for in the comparison
The three variants are designed to triangulate:

If all three pass and produce similar results with high cross-variant correlation → trend-following on commodities is robust, signal choice doesn't matter much, pick the simplest one (Variant 1)
If Variants 2 and 3 pass but Variant 1 fails → simple price-based trend doesn't capture commodity dynamics; need more sophisticated signals
If Variant 1 passes but 2 and 3 fail → don't add complexity, simple wins
If variants pass in different sectors (e.g., Variant 1 works in energy, Variant 2 in metals) → may need hybrid signal logic, or commodities aren't homogeneous enough for one rule
If all three fail → commodity trend doesn't work in our sample as we've specified it; either the universe is wrong or the trend approach doesn't transfer

The deliverable is interpretable findings, not just headline numbers.
What we are NOT doing

No parameter tuning. The signal definitions are locked. If 50/200 doesn't work for Variant 1, we don't try 30/100 or 70/250. The verdict is the verdict.
No basket modification mid-test. The 13 instruments are locked. We don't drop the bad performers to make the basket look better.
No regime overlays in this first round. We're testing pure trend signals. Regime filters can come later if a variant earns it.
No leverage beyond the vol-targeting. The portfolio targets 15% vol; we don't lever to 30% to see if returns scale.

